column168: At 1707 hours on December 2, 2014, I, John Vergis, was called by our dispatcher to inform me that a conductor walking his train in our Rook Yard heard what seemed like a venting noise coming from the top of tank car SHQX 50283.  I immediately called a transloading contractor, Rail Loading Services, who was already on property working for Centennial Energy to go look at the car.  He called me back and informed me that the Liquid valve on the A end of the car was leaking.  As he investigated, he found that both the liquid valve plugs and the vapor valve plug was loose along with the sample line plug.  He tried to tighten the valve handle on the leaking liquid valve but the leak would not stop.  He put Teflon Tape on the valve plug and then installed the plug and tightened it, and then the leak stopped. He also installed tape on the other plugs and tightened them.  The car was then set to Centennials Transload Track in our Rook Yard track and then will be transloaded into another car.
column169: Cars need to be better inspected when being prepared for shipment.

Madelvis Cronkhite/  Alaska Airlines Cargo Lead 907-474-9186 ext 1.

At 0105 ET hours, David Elliott of R&L carriers contacted ERTS regarding the suspected release of an unknown amount of a UN3082 OCTAMAR BT25 ( Naphtha Solution) in the rear of a trailer at the Hartford, CT terminal. At the time of this report, no drains, soils or waterways were reported as being impacted. The caller stated there was an unknown amount of liquid under the pails of this product on the trailer and crews reported a heavy odor from the trailer. The caller stated there was no evidence of any damage to the containers, but requested a contractor be dispatched to investigate. Based on not having a confirmed release of a haz mat, ERTS will wait until confirmation of a release prior to making any regulatory reporting. ERTS has dispatched a network contractor (ESI of CT) The contractor reports having an approximate ETA of 60 minutes A DOT5800 may be required for this incident. The shipper is Coty Enterprises.  The contractor stated that it appears the heavy freight loaded on top of the pail, dented/crushed the pail. resulting in the release. The contractor will continue to break down the pallet to check for any other damage

column168: During unloading operations at the R&L Carriers terminal, 1 - 55 gallon steel drum was apparently punctured by a fork on a forklift that resulted in a 20 gallon release to the trailer floor and adjacent loading dock. A contractor was dispatched and over packed the damaged drum to go back to the shipper for reclamation. All absorbent was was containerized and transported off site for pending disposal,

On December 2, 2014, an R&L Carriers terminal experienced a spill involving UN1866 Resin Solution "Polylite." Approximately 5-7 gallons released from (1) 55-gallon steel drum as the result of an apparent forklift puncture. The release impacted the trailer floor and the parking area below. No soils, drains or waterways were impacted by this release. Hulls Environmental responded out of Atlanta, GA to clean the release and overpack the damaged drum. All contaminated absorbents were containerized and the site was restored to its previous condition.

When the shipping tech put the nitrogen on the rail car to unload it, the cars pressure relief device opened, releasing a minimum amount of nitrogen. The shipping tech called the safety specialist to investigate and he went to the rail car. The shipping tech demonstrated what was happening and I advised him to not unload the car. Only about a 1/4 lb of nitrogen was released. The rail car is owned by Dow Chemical. We called Chemtrec, per Dow's instructions from the last incident involving one of their rail cars.After the report was made to Chemtrec, Dow contacted us and informed us that they were sending their in the field repair contractors to repair the pressure relief device. USES came onto our site and was able to fix a worn gasket that wasn't allowing the pressure relief device to seat properly.
column169: Will be filling a customer complaint with the Dow about their faulty gaskets on their rail cars

column168: At 0435 ET hours, Caleb Lindsey of R&L Carriers contacted ERTS regarding the release of approximately 5 (five) gallons of a UN1866 FLAMMABLE RESIN SOLUTION ( Derakane 411-350 ) from a 55 (fifty-five) gallon steel drum to the rear of a trailer at the Montebello CA terminal. At the time of this report, no drains, soils or waterways were reported as being impacted. The caller stated the release was visible when the trailer was received to be offloaded from the FON terminal and apparently was due to alack of blocking and bracing resulting in the release. ERTS has dispatched a network contractor ( K-VAC Env- Rancho Cucamonga, CA ) to respond. The contractor ETA will be posted once confirmed. ERTS has requested copies of the BOL & MSDS. A DOT5800 may be required for this incident. As required, ERTS notified the CA EMA and Blake acknowledged receipt of the incident as issued RTN 14-7003. The material was released from a damaged seam on the drum from transit.

During transportation, it was identified that 1 345 gallon steel tote of NA1993 Combustible Liquids was damaged and released an estimated 30 gallons to the trailer floor and pavement. A contractor was dispatched to the site and they secured the damaged valve on the tote and cleaned up the released product with absorbents. The damaged tote was taken back to the Chicago terminal and placed in the OS&D Department pending further instructions from the shipper. All waste was containerized and transported off site for pending disposal.

It was discovered during unloading operations at the terminal that 1 fiberboard box  with 4-1 gallon poly containers of UN1760 Corrosive Liquids, n.o.s. was damaged by other freight that resulted in 2 of the 4 containers to be punctured and resulted in the subsequent 2 gallon release to the trailer floor only. A contractor was dispatched and cleaned up the impacted trailer floor. All waste was containerized and left on site for pending disposal. The good containers were over packed and left at the terminal to either be sent to the consignee or returned to the shipper for reclamation.

column168: On December 8, 2014, a CTL Distribution 407 tanker trailer experienced a leak during unloading operations at Schlitterbahn Water Park in Galveston, TX. Approximately 63 gallons of UN1791 Sodium Hypochlorite was determined to be released as the result of the tanker dome-lid not being sufficiently secured during pressurization for unloading. The released product migrated into a nearby waterway that was confirmed to lead into the Galveston Bay. USES responded out of Texas City, TX to contain and clean the released product. A 150 ft. section of the waterway was boomed off and contained. The Coast Guard had also responded to the site once it was confirmed that the material had reached the waterway. Per their instruction, USES removed approximately 4,000 gallons of bleach-impacted waters for pending disposal in a frac tank on-site. Additionally, approximately 10 yards of solid waste was generated for pending disposal from the impacted soils. All contaminated soils were removed from the site; the site was restored to its original condition.

Another shipment in the vicinity was being loaded by forklift, when the forklift blade protruded and punctured a drum, causing it to leak half of its' contents onto the dock.  The drum was immediately uprighted.  After donning the appropriate personal protective equipment, the drum was overpacked by the dock crew into a suitable salvage drum, along with the cleaning compound used to clean the material from the dock.  The shipment was then loaded into a trailer destined to the intended waste disposal facility without further incident.  The incident was reported to the State of Maryland--1040 12-12-14.
column169: The forklift operator was a new employee.  He was immediately taken off the job and given additional training in proper forklift operations.

At 0130 ET hours, Rich Kaczynski of A Duie Pyle Trucking contacted ERTS regarding a suspected mechanical failure to a tractor trailer resulting in the fully involved fire of both the tractor and trailer near Lafayette, NY. At the time of this report, no drains, soils or waterways were reported as being impacted. As required, ERTS notified the NY DEC and Dispatcher 30 acknowledged receipt of the incident and RTN # 1408920 was issued. The caller stated the driver reported a mechanical issue and the fire resulted. The caller stated the cargo is hazardous listed as approximately 20,000 pounds of UN3349 6.1 (PG3) PYRETHROID PESTICIDE SOLID. ERTS contacted the driver on site and was advised that the roadway is closed in both directions and HAZMAT and local FD are on scene and allowing the fire to burn itself out. The EMA & FD are considering a local evacuation of approximately 1/2 mile. The driver also reported local EMS is treating several people that were stuck in traffic, down wind for nausea and vomiting. ERTS notified the NRC and P/O Threatt acknowledged receipt of the incident and issued RTN# 1102466.  The FD will allow the trailer fire to burn itself out. The waste in 2 roll-off will be staged at the nearby NYSDOT yard until profile and disposal is approved.

Heritage Transport driver was at the customer site to load their material.  Driver hooked the hoses to the customer's tank and began to pump the material into our tanker.  A reaction occurred and caused a cloud to form.  The cloud up into the customer's plant.  The scrubbers appeared to not be working properly and the plant was evacuated.  The fire department was called and by 3:00 p.m., the area was declared ok.  The investigation is still ongoing and as we learn more, we will update the report.    THE HERITAGE TRANSPORT, LLC (HT) DRIVER ARRIVED AT THE SITE AT APPROXIMATELY 9:15 A.M. AND FOLLOWED THE PROCEDURES OF WEIGHING IN AND PROCEEDED TO DOOR 13 ON THE BACK SIDE OF THE BUILDING.  THE DRIVER BACKED THE TANKER IN AND AONNED THE NECESSARY PPE; RUBBER JACKET, HARD HAT, AND FACE SHIELD.    AT 9:45 A.M., THE DRIVER ENGAGED THE VACUUM PUMP, HOOKED THE VACUUM HOSE UP, AND STARTED PULLING VAC.  THE DRIVER PROCEEDED TO HOOK UP THE EXHAUST HOSE WHICH RUNS BACK INTO THE BUILDING INTO A DRUM OF WATER.  THE DRIVER WENT AROUND TO THE BACK SIDE OF THE TANKER AND HOOKED UP 2" HOSE FROM THE CUSTOMER'S FITTING TO THE TRACTOR.  THE DRIVER PROCEEDED TO TURN VALVES ON AND STARTED TO PUMP THE MATERIAL INTO TANKER.  THE DRIVER WALKED DOWN TO THE OTHER END OF THE TRUCK, AND PACED BACK AND FORTH TO MONITOR THE LOADING PROCESS.    THE DRIVER NOTICED AN ORANGE CLOUD COMING OUT FROM THE DRUM WHERE THE EXHAUST WAS.  THE DRIVER DONNED HIS RESPIRATOR AND BEGAN TO SHUTDOWN EVERYTHING.  THE DRIVER CONTACTED THE CUSTOMER AND INSTRUCTED THEM TO EVACUATE.  AT THAT POINT THE CUSTOMER BEGAN THEIR EMERGENCY PROCEDURES AND EVACUATED THE PLANT.    DURING THE INVESTIGATION IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THE TANKER, WHILE EMPTY, HAD NOT BEEN ADEQUATELY RINSED WHICH RESULTED IN A RESIDUE REMAINING FROM THE LAST LOAD ON THE TRAILER (RQ, UN1760, WASTE CORROSIVE LIQUIDS, N.O.S., 8, PGII, (NITRIC ACID/AMMONIUM BIFLUORIDE), (D007, D002). THE RESIDUE RESULTING IN A NOX RELEASE WHEN LOADING COMMENCED ON THE TANKER TRAILER WITH A DIFFERENT CONSIGNMENT (RQ, UN3264, WASTE CORROSIVE LIQUID, ACIDIC, INORGANIC, N.O.S., 8, PG II, (PHOSPHORIC ACID).
column169: Investigation is still ongoing.    TO PREVENT RECURRENCE OF SUCH AN EVENT THE FOLLOWING CORRECTIVE ACTIONS HAVE/WILL BE IMPLEMENTED:    -IMPROVED CLEANING PROCESS FOR CONSIGNMENTS CONTAINING NITRIC ACID THAT INCLUDES HIGH PRESSURE RINSING AT ALL ACCESSIBLE MANWAYS FOLLOWED BY WASHING WITH HIGH PRESSURE SPINNER SYSTEM.    -REVISE TRANKER TRAILER VISUAL PROCESS AFTER RINSING/CLEANING PROCEDURES.    -INSTALL BOOSTER PUMP TO INCREASE WATER PRESSURE FOR RINSING PURPOSES AT AN LOADING STATION.

column168: A FRA inspector reported tank car GATX 54151 in the railyard dripping commodity from its bottom outlet valve (BOV). Inspection of GATX 54151 by a BNSF mechanical/hazardous material responder revealed that the BOV operating handle was in the closed position, pinned and sealed. The responder reported finding the bottom outlet valve's closure cap (BOC) 3/4 turn from being tool tight and the responder tool tightened the BOC which ended the slow commodity drip from the BOC's threaded connection by 1715 hrs. CST, 12/02/2014. All spillage evaporated. The BOC gasket condition was not inspected.

column168: Driver was taking full load (4500 gallons) of diesel fuel to a well pad, lost control of truck on curve, remembers truck flopping over, ending up over guard rail. He reported incident to his supervisor who in turn reported it to me. I then began sequence of calls to emergency cleanup company (BBU of Lancaster, Ohio), then Ohio EPA, then National Response, then our own people to respond to incident. When truck went over guard rail, lid(s) were damaged on top of tank and let fuel seep at a steady rate. Absorbents were place to prevent fuel from traveling to well and nearby creek. Emergency cleanup company arrived, our own equipment and people arrived and pumped the majority of fuel into one of own trucks. It was not contaminated. Cleanup company began to remediate area as soon as truck was removed. The soil was removed, well was tested, temporary water source was brought in for property owners until well is certified safe to use. Replacement of soil and seeding will take place as soon as weather permits.
column169: Driver is undergoing retraining, including class room and practical road tests to assure he is fit to drive tanker vehicles. Better preplanning of routes and delivery timing will be implemented.

column168: Our fuel truck driver overfilled an aboveground storage tank on Dec 9 2014 in Greenville, SC. The customer (J Grady Randolph) is a trucking company and they own a 12000 gallon diesel tank at the site. The tank had an overfill alarm but it was not operating correctly and did not go off when the tank reached capacity. As a result the tank was overfilled by our driver and approximately 75 gallons of diesel fuel spilled onto the ground. In house staff and a spill responder (Carolina Emergency Response Team- CERT) were notified and began clean up immediately. The South Carolina Department of Health and Environmental Controls (SCDHEC) was notified and visited the site the following day to confirm clean up and response activity. The fuel was contained in the dirt/gravel area around the tank and did not reach any drains or waterways. The ground was excavated and disposed of by the spill responder (CERT) per state and federal requirements.
column169: Our staff is reviewing operating procedures to determine additional steps that can be taken to prevent overfills.

column168: On Friday December 5, 2014, Alaron Nuclear Services received a shipment (Alaron shipment #14-0559) consisting of customer equipment contained within two 20' sealand containers on a flatbed trailer.  The origin of the shipment was TOXCO Materials Management Center in Oak Ridge, TN for WMG, Inc. (TOXCO shipment #X140928)  The carrier was Interstate Ventures/Visionary.  Upon receipt inspection, it was noticed that one of the containers exhibited damage consisting of an approximately 7" "tear" in the metal wall near the floor-wall junction.  Radiological surveillance around the tear exhibited removable surface contamination in the amount of 12,000 dpm/100cm^2 beta-gamma.  The area on the container was decontaminated by wiping, container sealed with caulking, and moved to storage.  After removing the container from the trailer, the trailer was surveyed for contamination.  Two discrete areas of beta-gamma contamination measuring 20,000 cpm/probe and 2,000 cpm/probe (Ludlum Model 12A with a 16cm^2 pancake probe @ 10% efficiency) were identified on the trailer in the area directly below where the tear in the container was.  These discrete areas of contamination were captured with duct tape and moved to a radioactive waste disposal container.  In this same location, an area of contamination in the amount of 300-400 cpm/probe was found embedded in the wood of the trailer deck. The trailer was moved to controlled area, decontaminated by chiseling out the contamination, surveyed for unrestricted use in accordance with our procedural and license conditions, and released back to the carrier.

column168: A Clean Harbors Environmental Services Inc. driver discovered a leaking drum in transit from the shipper to the designated disposal facility. The driver immediately notified management and an in house response team was mobilized to the scene. The response team donned the proper PPE, located the leaking drum in the trailer, and over packed the drum into an approved salvage container. The drum was then transported to the original disposal facility without further incident. Montana Disaster & Emergency Services were notified - report# 14120701.
column169: At the time the driver accepted the drums for transportation no evidence of leaking was observed. The driver has been re-instructed to conduct a thorough inspection of each container before acceptance and if any evidence of a reduction in structural integrity is found to take the appropriate actions to either place the container into a suitable salvage drum, re containerize, or reject before transportation is initiated. In addition, the shipper has also been advised of the incident and instructed to verify the containerized waste being offered for transportation is loaded and secured in a manner that will prevent any potential risk to the containers by using proper load securement and pallet inspections.

Tank car GATX 57444 was reported emanating vapor from its top fitting area which had a Teflon material security bag applied over its valve housing area. GATX 57444 was cordoned-off. Response contractors arrived and inspected GATX 57444. The four flange bolts applied on the vapor line riser connection (below the T-piping assembly that held a horizontal vapor valve and a vertical ruptured disc assembly) appeared tight but allowed vapor to escape at this flange connection. Responder's loosened all flange bolt nuts and then tightened them to eliminate the vent at the flange connection. This process was repeated until the flange connection was fully seated, sealed and the venting ceased.  Ambient humidity resulted in vapor formed liquid droplets adhering to the valve housing area and on the security bag. The security bag was contaminated and earmarked for disposal. Corrosive material adhering on GATX 57444 was neutralized and wiped. Afterwards, a water/soap solution was applied around the flange connection to confirm that no further vapor leak was detectable.

column62: Missing Component or Device; Valve Open
column168: UTLX 210172 was reported to be releasing product from the top of the car.  Inspection of the car found the liquid valve open slightly and the cam-lock cap gasket deformed.  The valve was open due to the operating shaft being turned slightly past center.  This occurred because the valve handle was loose and did not engage the handle stop.  The cap gasket was replaced with a new one provided by the consignee.  The car was then released to continue to destination.
column169: Ensure valves are close properly and gaskets are in proper condition prior to releasing car.

column168: Our driver picked up a shipper-loaded CTMV at the shipper.  Our driver was restricted from inspecting the top of the CTMV at the plant because of plant safety procedures.  After traveling about 300 miles, our driver stopped at a Truck stop and noticed HazMat on the sides of the CTMV.  Our driver found an open front washout port.  A cleanup contractor was dispatched clean up the release.  Since the contractor noticed minimal HazMat on the route to the truck stop, and the release stopped when the CTMV was parked, the release duration is estimated to be tens of minutes.  A replacement cap was installed without issues, so it is suspected that the missing washout port cap was either defective or installed incorrectly, and it dislodged enroute due to surging and sloshing.  QC Reference 44072.

According to the information obtained, the following occurred.  Tractor-tanker unit roll over as a result of an accident.  As a result, approximately 1000 gallons of product were released and impacted soil.  ERS, Inc. was dispatched to perform the cleanup and assist with off-loading the tanker.    The remaining product was transferred into a new tanker.  ERS, Inc. recovered the free liquids with a vacuum truck and excavated an area of contaminated soil approximately 3 feet wide by 100 feet long.  ERS, Inc. will coordinate disposal of the waste generated as a result of the incident.
column169: Since the release was accidental, no plans currently exist to prevent recurrence.  However, Hauenstein Trucking, Inc. will continue to reinforce safety guidelines and handling procedures to all personnel.

column168: On 12/6/2014 minutes prior to 6:20am driver was traveling east in extremely heavy fog on I-40 Service Road attempting a right turn to travel south on CR2180. Driver's tractor began to make the turn, however the rear passenger tires on the trailer left the road 8' prior to start of the turn. This resulted in the trailer ending up 6' off the road which contained about a 5' culvert. Then at 6:20am vehicle overturned onto the passenger side. Fuel began to slowly drip out of the top hatches on compartment 2 and 5. Buckets were placed under the leaking hatches to mitigate the effects of the release.
column169: Administrative Solution - Incident share during January safety meetings. Continue to implement more drivers into the Smith System Defensive Driver Training // Employee Solution - Employee's status and qualification is under review. Safety share on trailer tracking.

column168: A van trailer containing various shipments of hazardous waste picked up that day arrived at the intermediate truck transfer facility for unloading and reloading into other trailers destined for various intended waste disposal facilities.  Upon opening the door, a puddle was noticed on the trailer floor.  A response crew was summoned, donned the appropriate personal protective equipment and entered the trailer.  A drum had begun leaking from the bottom seam.  It was overpacked into a suitable salvage container and the cleaning compound used to clean the trailer floor was also placed inside.  The shipment was then loaded onto a trailer destined for the intended waste disposal facility without further incident.
column169: The shipment had just been picked up from a location less than 3 miles away.  Although the drum was not leaking when picked up, it was used and showed signs of age.  The driver was instructed to use better care inspecting drums.  The shipper was notified of the incident and also advised to use better care when loading old used drums.

column168: On December 19, 2014 at 18:47 hours, personnel at CSXT Barr Yard discovered ELCX 2601, a loaded UN 1105, Pentanols tank car to have released product from the bottom outlet valve area. The car was isolated and the Shipper, BASF Corp. was notified via CHEMTREC, report 2014-12-19-00158. A CSX Emergency Response contractor, Sunpro, the Schererville, IN branch office was dispatched to the scene. Upon inspection it was determined the bottom outlet valve gasket was deteriorated.  As a preventative measure the valve/pin was re-set and the cap was tightened which stopped the leak.     A HAZMATHOLD was placed on ELCX 2601 and will require an OTMA to continue in transportation to the consignee to be unloaded.     Cause Code: 148 at 5 points   NARRI: 2 (5 + 1 + 0) x (2 + 0) = 24

Reportedly there was evidence of dried product around the pressure relief vent and the frangible disk was suspected to be ruptured. The tank car was isolated and the shipper, Honeywell Inc., was notified via Chemtrec, report #2014-1219-00145 . Summit Environmental, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the Hawthorne Yard. column58: Bottom Outlet Valve; Bottom Outlet Valve
column168: On 12/23/2014 at 13:00 hours, CSX personnel discovered TILX 191166, a loaded tank car of Petroleum Crude Oil, releasing product from the bottom outlet valve. The car was isolated and shipper, UET Shipping LLC from Bismarck, ND, was notified. CHEMTREC Report number was issued: 2014-12-23-00125. Sunpro, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found that the bottom outlets valve was in the downward position and that the securement pin was not inside the holder. The project manager also observed that the packing bolts were loose, and the bottom outlet valves handle was worn about a fourth of the way through. The project manager removed the bottom outlet cap and noted that the gasket was deteriorating .  The response team installed a new gasket and tightened the packing bolts. SUNPRO secured the bottom outlet cap and sealed the bottom outlet handle with ONESEAL #24015667 and the securement pin with ONESEAL #24015675. The project manager noted that the leak had stopped.      Cause Code: 535 at 5 nar points  NARRI: 5 (5 + 5 + 0) (2 + 0) = 100
column169: No additional comments.

column168: On December 26th, 2014 at 05:48 hours, personnel in the CSXT Frontier Yard discovered TILX 351629, a loaded UN 1267, Petroleum Crude Oil tank car to have wetness down the sides of the tank car coming from around the manway. The car was isolated and the Shipper, Freepoint Commodities, LLC, was notified via CHEMTREC, report 2014-12-26-00009. A CSX Emergency Response contractor, EP+S of Vermont the Buffalo branch was dispatched to the scene, upon inspection it was determined that the release was from the manway cover, all manway cover swing bolts where less than tool tight, the manway cover gasket was inspected and found a crack in the gasket, the gasket was replaced.  The nozzle, manway cover and tank car were wiped down and the cover was re-secured tool tight.  Mr. Rocco Wall, with Freepoint Commodities, LLC., cell 973-216-7575 was notified of the situation found and the corrective action taken. TILX 351629 was released for transport.    This incident DID require a special move.    Cause Code: 200 (5 points) and 209 (5 points)  NARRI: 5x(5+5+0)x(2+0) = 100

column168: A solid waste ladened gondola CIGX 803328 was reported dripping a brownish colored oily liquid substance in the railyard. Responders inspecting CIGX 803328 suspected water from recent rain events co-mingled with material inside the gondola and was dripping out from the gondolas bottom weep-holes.  Plastic sheeting and buckets were placed under CIGX 803328 to catch further dripping of this oily liquid substance. No solid material was observed leaking. Afterwards, CIGX 803328 was wrapped in plastic sheeting to prevent any additional rain water from entering the gondola. The waste lading loader described the packaging inside the gondola as 13.7 cubic yard capacity lift bags (super sacks) of 7 ounce woven polypropylene industrial fabric with Velcro closures. The inner liners of these lift bags consisted of two 6 mil thick polyethylene liners. The gondola was lined with 6 mil thick polyethylene fabric coated (both sides) with 1.5 mil thick polyethylene coating also with Velcro closures. In addition, a moisture barrier consisting of plastic sheeting also lined the gondola. On 12/12-13/2014, the shipper-loader responders removed the lift bags from CIGX 803328 and placed them into lined roll-off bins/trucks for furtherance. A couple of breaches in the exterior liner covering the lift bags were observed. Once emptied, CIGX 803328's interior was cleaned. Captured spillage and spent cleaning materials were placed into disposal drums and earmarked for appropriate disposal. The root cause of non-solidified waste material leaching through the lift bags and/or rain water incursion is pending.
column169: No additional comments.

column168: A solid waste ladened gondola CIGX 803341 was reported dripping a brownish colored liquid substance in the railyard. Responders inspecting CIGX 803341 suspected water from recent rain events co-mingled with material inside the gondola and was dripping out from the gondola's bottom weep-holes.  Absorbent padding was placed under CIGX 803341 to catch drips. No solid material was observed leaking. The waste lading loader described the packaging as 13.7 cubic yard capacity lift bags (super sacks) of 7 ounce woven polypropylene industrial fabric with Velcro closures. The inner liners of these lift bags consisted of two 6 mil thick polyethylene liners. The gondola was lined with 6 mil thick polyethylene fabric coated (both sides) with 1.5 mil thick polyethylene coating also with Velcro closures. In addition, a moisture barrier consisting of plastic sheeting also lined the gondola. Responders covered the gondola with plastic sheeting to protect the lading from additional moisture from a pending rain event. The bottom weep-holes in CIGX 803341 were plugged along with other observed dripping pathways. On 12/13/2014, CIGX 803341 was returned to the nearby shipper. Impacted ballast in the railyard was placed into a disposal drum along with spent absorbent padding. The drum was earmarked for appropriate disposal. The root cause of non-solidified waste material leaching through the lift bags and/or rain water incursion is pending.

column168: Tank car BN 875099 staged in a temporary storage track was reported dripping commodity from its bottom outlet valve (BOV) area. A BNSF mechanical responder closed BN 875099's partially open top operated bottom outlet valve's (TOBOV) operating rod by 3/4 turn.  In addition, the BOV mounting flange bolts were tool tightened. During the BOV flange bolt securement process, the responder reported that two flange bolts were broken. Afterwards, the leak at the BOV flange connection ceased. The outage in BN 875099 was gauged to estimate the possible commodity loss in transportation. A remediation contractor excavated and removed impacted soils followed by appropriate disposal.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column169: Shipper must properly inspect and secure containers before they are released for transportation.

column168: CHS was delivering anhydrous ammonia to a mobile converter which was owned by Blick's enterprises. One of Blick's employees drug a hose on the ground which had a valve attached to the end. The dragging of the hose caused the valve to open and release anhydrous ammonia. 7 tons or 14,000 lbs. of NH3 escaped before the valve was able to be closed. 12 houses were evacuated with 3 people at home at the time. Once the release was stopped, the homeowners were allowed to return to their homes.  No injuries resulted as a result of this release. MN state highway 251 was closed for approximately 2 hours as well. CHS Transportation was not the RP in this incident as we were delivering the product and had just pulled in to unload. This may be a duplicate report on this incident as the RP reported this incident as well. MN Department of Agriculture and MN DOT Hazmat team also responded to this incident.
column169: The RP (Blick's) designed a bulk head and revised their procedures to ensure an incident of this type does not re-occur.

After a shipment of solid waste in lift bags (super sacks) loaded in a gondola was reported leaking liquid on the BNSF, other like shipments in gondolas on the BNSF were identified and inspected for liquid leakage.  CIGX 803344 was inspected and reported leaking liquid from this gondola's weep-holes. No solid material was observed leaking. The waste lading loader described the packaging inside the gondola as 13.7 cubic yard capacity lift bags (super sacks) of 7 ounce woven polypropylene industrial fabric with Velcro closures. The inner liners of these lift bags consisted of two 6 mil thick polyethylene liners. The gondola was lined with 6 mil thick polyethylene fabric coated (both sides) with 1.5 mil thick polyethylene coating also with Velcro closures. In addition, a moisture barrier consisting of plastic sheeting also lined the gondola. Contract responders wrapped the gondola in plastic sheeting to contain the leaks. On 12/17-18/2014, the shipper-loader removed the lift bags from CIGX 803344 and placed them into trucks for furtherance.  Once emptied, CIGX 803344's interior was cleaned. Ground spillage was remediated. Impacted ballast, plastic sheeting and spent cleaning materials were place into disposal drums and earmarked for appropriate disposal. The root cause of non-solidified waste material leaching through the lift bags and/or rain water incursion is pending.
column169: No additional comments.

After a shipment of solid waste in lift bags (super sacks) loaded in a gondola was reported leaking liquid on the BNSF, other like shipments in gondolas on the BNSF were identified and inspected for liquid leakage.  CIGX 803339 was inspected and reported leaking liquid from this gondola's weep-holes. No solid material was observed leaking. The waste lading loader described the packaging inside the gondola as 13.7 cubic yard capacity lift bags (super sacks) of 7 ounce woven polypropylene industrial fabric with Velcro closures. The inner liners of these lift bags consisted of two 6 mil thick polyethylene liners. The gondola was lined with 6 mil thick polyethylene fabric coated (both sides) with 1.5 mil thick polyethylene coating also with Velcro closures. In addition, a moisture barrier consisting of plastic sheeting also lined the gondola. Contract responders wrapped the bottom of the gondola in plastic sheeting to contain the leaks. On 12/19/2014, the shipper-loader removed the lift bags from CIGX 803339 and placed them into trucks for furtherance.  Once emptied, CIGX 803339's interior was cleaned. Ground spillage was remediated. Impacted ballast, plastic sheeting and spent cleaning materials were place into disposal drums and earmarked for appropriate disposal. The root cause of non-solidified waste material leaching through the lift bags and/or rain water incursion is pending.
column169: No additional comments.

column58: Pressure Relief Valve or Device - Reclosing; Vapor Valve
column168: After being weighed in the railyard, tank car GAMX 9740 was reported being overloaded by weight (beyond its maximum gross weight on rail). On 12/11/2014, GAMX 9740 was reported venting in the railyard. The initial responder inspecting GAMX 9740 reported finding ice accumulating on its vapor valve. The vapor valve was found partially open with its closure plug not tool tight. The responder closed the vapor valve and tool tightened its closure plug which ended the vapor release from the vapor valve assembly. Afterwards, contract responders re-inspected GAMX 9740 and reported observing intermittent vapor releases from GAMX 9740's pressure plate connection and its 300 psig reclosing pressure relief valve (PRV) which indicated that internal pressure within GAMX 9740 was increasing. GAMX 9740 was isolated in railyard for commodity reduction and was continuously monitored. On 12/12/2014, a portion of the commodity within GAMX 9740 was transferred into a tanker truck without incident by 1600 hrs. CST.  Afterwards the internal pressure within GAMX 9740 dropped from 289 psi to 60 psi ending any further venting or vapor releases. Eight pressure plate mounting bolts at the previous intermittent vent location were tool tightened 1/2 turn each. It was also noted that GAMX 9740's magnetic gaging device was not functioning properly as it was portraying inaccurate commodity levels.     Qualification stenciling on GAMX 9740 indicated GAMX 9740's last tank qualification date was in year 2012 and PRD qualification in year 2014.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings, including appropriate commodity outage and filling limits.

column168: On December 31st at 1925 hours personnel in the CSXT Bostic Yard discovered TCBX197078, a loaded tank car of Alcohols, N.O.S. leaking from bottom of car. The car was isolated and the shipper, Renewable Products Marketing were notified via CHEMTREC report number 2014-1231-00138.  SWS Environmental, a CSXT response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found the cause of the release was due to a deteriorated bottom outlet cap gasket.  The issue identified and corrective actions were communicated to Renewable Products representative Kevin Brim at 952-465-3220. Contractor personnel replaced the bottom outlet cap gasket and properly tightened the secondary closure.  The leak was secured and the car released for transport. This incident did require a special switching move.    5(5+3+0) x (2+0) = 80 NARRI  NAR Cause Code 580 - Bottom Outlet Cap Gasket Deteriorated

column168: AFTER AN UNLOADER DROPPED A HAZMAT PACKAGE ONTO THE IRREG CHUTE AT DOOR 14, IT BOUNCED OFF & HIT A BOLT THAT WAS PROTRUDING FROM THE FLOOR. THE BOLT PUNCTURED THE BOX & ONE OF THE BOTTLES INSIDE, SO A PUDDLE BEGAN FORMING, AROUND THE BOX. A SUPERVISOR SAW IT AND IMMEDIATELY NOTIFIED THE DESIGNATED RESPONDERS. WHEN I ARRIVED TO THE AREA, I UTILIZED THE SILVER SHIELD RESPONSE SHEETS TO ASSESS THE SITUATION. BECAUSE THE PACKAGE WAS CORROSIVE, I ALTERED MY PPE TO INCLUDE THE SILVER SHIELD INNER LINERS BEFORE TESTING THE PH OF THE LIQUID. THE PH WAS APPROX 12.1 CONTAINERIZED THE LEAKING BOX INTO A LINED SPILL TRAY. I THEN USED SODIUM BICARBONATE TO NEUTRALIZE THE LIQUID. I RETESTED THE PH TO ENSURE THAT IT WAS WITHIN THE 6-9 RANGE. THEN I USED CLAY-BASED ABSORBENT TO SOLIDIFY ANY REMAINING LIQUID. I SWEPT UP ALL CONTAMINATED MATERIALS & PUT THEM INTO ANOTHER LINED SPILL TRAY. I THEN TOOK THE PACKAGE TO THE DMP AREA FOR FURTHER PROCESSING.  UPON EXAMINATION, I FOUND THAT 1 BOTTLE WAS PUNCTURED & THE OTHER 3 WERE SOILED.

column168: The Giant Resource Recovery (GRR) Rail Head facility is a 10-day transfer facility. On December 3, 2014, a leak was observed coming from a roll-off container holding solid hazardous waste material. The roll-off container was moved from the ground and positioned on top of plastic on a concrete slab. Catch pans were placed beneath the container along with absorbent material to collect the leaking material. The leak was stopped/contained approximately 30 minutes after the time it was observed. Potentially impacted soil beneath the roll-off was excavated the same day and placed in drums for disposal.The material within the roll-off container was shifted within the container to allow access to the back door. The back door was opened (without any additional release of material), the rear seal was cleaned, and silicone was added to enhance the seal. The silicone was allowed to dry, and the back door of the container was closed. No further leaks were observed following the repair.All remaining materials utilized in the response activity (e.g., plastic, absorbent) were also placed in drums to await disposal.
column169: The use of a liner within the roll-off container may improve the capability of this container to hold any liquid materials that maybe present.GRR will continue to conduct daily inspections of containers.

column168: At approximately 13:45, Unit 1 was travelling eastbound on 91st Street towing a trailer containing compressed hydrogen.  Unit 1 departed the road to the right and travelled approximately 65 feet before rolling approximately one quarter times. Unit 1 impacted a fence and travelled approximately 36 feet.  Unit 1 then impacted a utility pole and came to rest on the roadside.  Local fire and police were dispatched and secured the scene and maintained intial isolation distance per the emergency response guidebook.  Airgas emergency response personnel arrived on scene to assist and determine the condition of the trailer.  "Bubbler" type neck leaks were identified on tubes 5 and 10.  Bubbler indicates that lead detection fluid bubbled continuously but not rapidly (approximately 1 cc/10 sec).  The leaks occurred for approximately 3 hours.  An LEL monitor was placed above the leaks to determine atmospheric hazards due to the flammability of hydrogen.  The LEL monitor never exceeded 7% of LEL.  The decision was made to transfill the two leaking tubes into an empty hydrogen tube trailer.  Once complete, the Airgas personnel checked the tubes for leaks again and found none.  The LEL in the atmosphere was also measured to be 0% of LEL.  After departure of the Unit 2, the tractor and trailer was uprighted by a crane and towing vehicles.  Unit 1 and tube trailer were then towed back to the Airgas facility.

column168: Veolia vehicle was at a customer site in Danielson, CT. While working at the customer location loading dock and parking area at 30 Rock Ave, Danielson, a Veolia employee noticed a small leak of liquid coming from another customer's 55-gallon drum that was previously loaded onto the vehicle. Upon closer inspection, it was determined that a drum of Trichloroethylene was slowly leaking on a bottom seam of the 55-gallon drum. Veolia reported this to the state of Connecticut DEEP (Environmental Agency) who also notified the local fire marshall of the leak. The location of the leak was the bottom seam of a 55-gallon drum. Duration of release was less than 1 hour. The leaking drum was removed from the vehicle and placed in an 85-gallon salvage drum and sent for appropriate disposal as originally contracted. A small footprint size stain on parking lot was cleaned up as well as a small amount of liquid that remained in the Veolia service box truck.
column169: In the future, Veolia employees will double check drums coming from this customer when offered for transportation. Veolia also notified customer of the issue and requested that they inspect drums/review drums for leaks in the future. Also, customer may want to follow up with their 55-gallon drum provider to make them aware of the issue.

column168: A FRA Hazardous Material Inspector inspecting tank car GATX 60949 in the railyard reported GATX 60949 had all four vapor/air line (blind) flange bolt nuts finger loose and one flange bolt nut (1 of 8) on the liquid line finger loose also. The FRA Inspector also reported that GATX 60949 was not actively leaking at the time of inspection, but commodity spillage had pooled atop GATX 60949 and some spillage had run down its side shell. No ground impact from spillage was reported. A BNSF mechanical responder secured all the loose flange bolt nuts by 1700 hrs. CST, 12/19/2014. A contractor neutralized and cleaned the spillage on GATX 60949 on 12/19/2014. The contact responders also inspected the fill hole securement on GATX 60949. The four fill hole securement bolt nuts were less than tool tight. The fill hole gasket was in place and serviceable.  The responders secured the fill hole and sealed it with seal numbered 24015620.

column168: Tank car UTLX 662270 in the railyard was reported with commodity on its top side shell. No ground impact from spillage was observed. UTLX 662270 was carefully moved and isolated in the railyard. Later on 12/24/2014, contract responders inspected UTLX 662270 and reported finding all 8 manway securement eyebolt nuts less than tool tight.  The manway gasket was in place and serviceable. The commodity outage was deemed appropriate.  Responders closed the manway lid and properly tool tightened all manway securement eyebolts nuts. All other valves and fittings were inspected and found secure. Intact shipper seals at the manway closure (Suncor 334291) and at the valve housing cover (Suncor 332022) were replaced by seals TIS 5941 and TIS 5942 respectively.   On 12/29/2014, the contract responders returned to clean/scrap the commodity spillage from UTLX 662270. All spent cleaning materials and removed commodity were placed into two disposal drums for appropriate future disposal.  Response was concluded by 1200 MST, 12/29/2014.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column168: Tank car MBLX 34407 in the railyard was reported emanating an odor. MBLX 34407 was cordoned-off in the railyard. Contract responders inspecting MBLX 34407 reported finding the B-end liquid valve 1/4 turn open with its closure plug not tool tight. Responders closed the B-end liquid valve and tool tightened its closure plug which ended the vapor/odor release at this closure plug orifice. column168: PVS-Nolwood delivery driver attempted to pump 50% sodium hydroxide from a tote to a customer tank. He hooked up the hoses in reverse and failed to vent the tote causing the source tote to pressurize and swell. He shut down the pump and attempted to vent the tote at the dome lid but was unable to do so. He pulled the cap from the standpipe. Material sprayed from the open stand pipe onto the customer's floor. The amount of material was less than 50 gallons. The tote serial number and latest test date was not recorded at the time of the incident. The release occurred as a result of employee error and inadequate training. The package performed satisfactorily and did not fail.

column162: DIRECTOR OF RISK MANAGEMENT AND LEGAL AFFAIRS
column168: On November 20, 2014, Geodis had a Marine Logistics Shipment tendered to us from shipper, US Joiner International, with instructions to have proper Dangerous Goods ("DG") packaging and declaration completed for the portion of the cargo that was hazardous. DG cargo consisted of UN1950 PG2.1 "Aerosol" cans. Unintentionally, the DG were tendered to Cathay Pacific Cargo ("Cathay") without proper DG packaging and declaration for final destination -Singapore. On Decembers, 2014, Geodis was made aware that the shipment was tendered to the airline as non-declared HAZMAT, Geodis immediately notified Cathay and requested cargo be stopped in Hong Kong. The entire cargo shipment (DG and general cargo) is currently being held at HKG under the control of the CAD.
column169: VOLUNTARY DISCLOSURE WAS IMMEDIATELY SENT TO THE FEDERAL AVIATION ADMINISTRATION ("FAA") ON DECEMBER 8, 2014. OUR MIAMI FACILITY WAS INSPECTED BY SPECIAL AGENT DANIELLE REZENDES OF THE FAA ON DECEMBER 16, 2015.  GEODIS IS CURRENTLY WAITING ON THE FINDINGS OF THE INVESTIGATION.  ADEQUATE REPRIMAND WILL BE ISSUED UPON CONCLUSION OF OUR CURRENT INTERNAL INVESTIGATION.  WE ARE ALSO IN THE PROCESS OF PREPARING AN INTERNAL INCIDENT AND DEVIATION REPORT DOCUMENTING OVERALL ISSUES AS WELL AS ALL ACTIONS TAKEN TO PREVENT THIS FROM HAPPENING AGAIN.

column168: At 11:35 hours during normal humping operations at the Belt Railway Clearing yard 6900 S. The car came out of the retarder lined for group #2, the lead trucks on the car started into the group and the rear trucks somehow became lined into Group #1 causing the car to derail and fall onto its side causing a puncture to tank car and causing approximately 4,000 gallons of denatured alcohol to leak to ground. Mansfield Oil Company monitors and controls the levels of LubeTech storage tanks via a computer generated electronic control system.  When needed, Mansfield Oil Company will contact LubeTech for approval and verification of the load that is needed.  On Wednesday, December 31, 2014, Nate Kovacevich ,  Mansfield Oil Company was seeing that the level in Tank #72 was reading 1000 gallons in a 40000 gallon tank.  Nate ordered a load of 7500 gallons of winter blend dyed diesel fuel to dispatch, John  Bodine with Ratzlaff Transport.  Upon policy, dispatcher with Ratzlaff Transport, John Bodine called LubeTech to ensure that the load would fit.  He was told that the load would fit with no problem.  The load was dispatched to driver Brian Pevito with Ratzlaff Transport.  After loading at Magellan Pipe Line in Roseville, MN. and arrival at LubeTech in Roseville, MN.  the driver, Brian Pevito contacted LubeTech personnel and got confirmation and approval of off loading into Tank #72.  He was told that there was plenty of room for delivery.  The volume was 1000 gallons for a delivery of 7500 gallons going into a 40000 gallon tank.        The delivery was made using the customer’s pump into a storage tank farm.  At the same time, there was a LubeTech driver employee delivering into another storage tank.  The storage tanks are equipped with an over-fill sound alarm when the tanks reach a certain height level.  When the alarm went off, Brian thought this was the alarm for the LubeTech driver’s delivery.  Brian was assured by all checks and responses that his load would definitely fit.  Immediately upon investigation all operations were shut down.         Three quarters completion of delivery it was noticed that the Tank #72 was overfilled. After shut down of delivery operations of unloading, Brian Pevito proceeded into operations of  LubeTech for notification of the incident.  He was informed by another LubeTech employee that this was all ready done and the appropriate emergency response was in place. Brian offered to help but was told by LubeTech that LubeTech would handle all clean-up.        John Orsucci, LubeTech Dispatch Manager did investigate after the incident and stated that when the driver, Brian Pevito with Ratzlaff Transport arrived, tank #72  had a reading of 1000 gallons.  This is a 40000 gallon tank.  John Orsucci also verified that when the fuel was spilling out of the top of tank #72, the electronic gauge did still read approximately 1000 gallons.       As stated before, LubeTech would handle all emergency response actions and clean-up.           WCEC Environmental Consultants - 1241 72nd Ave. NE - Fridley, MN was the company that LubeTech called for clean-up.  WCEC project number for this incident is 10404.  Estimation of spill was 200 gallons within the containment, 50 gallons outside of the containment onto snow and ground,  with clean up of 0.5 cubic yards of soil and snow that was recovered.
column169: Tank #72 was locked out until the electronic control system was repaired.  I have been told that this is now completed and working properly along with the manual level repaired as well.  It is recommended and training is now in place for all delivery drivers to also check the level after start up of delivery that the level gauge is indeed moving in the proper direction.  With these safe guards in place, this incident should never happen again.

column168: Tank car GLNX 34579 in the railyard was reported emanating an ammonia odor. GLNX 34579 was cordoned-off in the railyard. BNSF mechanical/hazardous material responders inspecting GLNX 34579 reported finding the A-end liquid valve approximately 1/2 turn open and liquid commodity seeping from its valve stem. column168: The trailer was identified as leaking on our Schneider property in Houston, Tx.  The leak was identified as coming through a seam in the outter jacket of the trailer.  We used our external emergency response team to help transfer the product (using vapor recovery) into a new trailer due to the nature of the product combined with the potent vapors.  The trailer has not been inspected to date and remains down for repairs.  The source of the leak is yet to be determined and could be anything from a true leak in the barrel, to a crack in a weld, to a damaged washout port.  This is perplexing as not only did the trailer go through its annual inspecton at the beginning of December but this load requires a special prep where the entire trailer must be pressure tested.  Not only do we perform this pressure test but it also recieves another pressure test at the shipping location.  Any leaks should have been observed at those times.
column169: I will update this log when we learn the true source of the leak.  I can't give an official recommendation until we know the sure source of the leak.  On a seperate note we feel the processes we have in place between ourselves and the shipper are sound and that this is an isolated incident.  Never the less we'll take appropriate follow up actions as warranted when the source is determined.

column168: ON DECEMBER 18, 2014, A MECHANICAL INSPECTION OF TANK CAR NATX 230580 IN THE TACOMA RAIL CLASSIFICATION YARD REVEALED COMMODITY STAINING RUNNING DOWN BOTH SIDES OF THE CAR FROM THE TOP VALVE AREA. THE CAR WAS CAREFULLY MOVED TO A SIDE TRACK WHERE FURTHER DETERMINATION OF THE CAUSE OF THE LEAK COULD BE MADE. I CONTACTED FRA INSPECTOR RANDY BOYINGTON FOR GUIDANCE. INSPECTOR BOYINGTON RESPONDED AND MADE AND INSPECTION OF TOP OF THE TANK CAR. HE FOUND THAT THE BOLTS ON THE UNLOADING CONNECTION PIPE FLANGE WERE VERY LOOSE. THE BOLTS WERE TIGHTENED AND MADE SAFE FOR MOVEMENT TO THE CUSTOMER US OIL TO BE UNLOADED. INSPECTOR BOYINGTON ADVISED THAT THE TANK CAR WOULD HAVE TO BE WASHED BEFORE IT CAN BE INTERCHANGED. FURTHERMORE, INSPECTOR BOYINGTON SAID THAT THE CAR WOULD HAVE TO HAVE AN OTMA TO BE MOVED TO WHERE REPAIRS COULD BE MADE TO THE UNLOADING VALVE BOLTS AND TO HAVE A PRESSURE TEST. TANK CAR WILL BE WASHED ON OR ABOUT 1/17/15 AT TACOMA RAIL. WE WON'T KNOW THE COST OF CLEANING UNTIL IT IS FINISHED AS THE CONTRACTOR CHARGES BY THE HOUR. I WILL ESTIMATE $1400.00 WHICH INCLUDES WAITING CHARGES AND CREW TIME FOR HANDLING THE CAR TO AND FROM WASH RACK.
column169: IT APPEARS THAT THERE IS AT LEAST A POSSIBILITY THAT WHEREVER THE TANK AR WAS LAST LOADED, THAT THE UNLOADING VALVE WAS UNBOLTED AND REMOVED FOR THE TEMPORARY PLACEMENT OF AN ALTERNATIVE CONNECTOR TYPE. THE BOLTS WERE LIKELY INADVERTENTLY LEFT LOOSE WHEN THE STOCK EQUIPMENT WAS REINSTALLED, THUS CAUSING THE LEAK.  SHIPPER MUST ENSURE THAT THEY PROPERLY UTILIZE LOADING VALVES AND THE SHIPPER NEEDS TO DO AN ADEQUAE PRE-TRIP INSPECTION OF ALL VALVES AND FITTINGS TO MAKE CERTAIN TANK CARS ARE SAFE FOR MOVEMENT.

column62: Loose Closure, Component, or Device; Missing Component or Device
column168: Tank car GATX 3027 was reported leaking from its manway closure while in the railyard. Initial inspection by a BNSF mechanical responder revealed that the manway securement eyebolt nuts were loose. A response contractor was called to finalized securement and clean spillage off of GATX 3027. Contract responders reported no shipper seal at the manway closure, the manway securement eyebolt nuts were not tool tight and the manway gasket was missing. A new 20 inch manway nozzle gasket was installed and the manway securement eyebolt nuts were properly tool tightened. Seal numbered 9707675 was applied at the manway closure.  Spillage on GATX 3027 was neutralized and wiped. Observed ground spillage was treated with an application of Micro-Blaze. All spent cleaning materials were placed into a 30 gallon poly disposal drum and earmarked for appropriate disposal.  Response was concluded by 1350 hrs. CST, 12/27/2014.

column25: SIMONS PETROLEUM LLC, DBA PILOT LOGISTICS SERVICES
column168: On December 22, 2014 at 00:40 company transport driver was traveling southbound on BIA 17, approximately 5 miles SE of County Road 22. This is approximately 20 miles SE of Manderee, North Dakota. Driver indicated that the road conditions suddenly became very icy and slick. He observed that his tanker trailer was sliding to the side. He attempted to correct the situation, but was unable to do so before the trailer struck the guardrail. The tractor and trailer then slid off the road and rolled 1.25 times. The resting position of the tanker trailer caused diesel fuel to leak from the trailer vent and a small rupture in tanker compartment on the side of the trailer that was resting on the ground. The product was contained by creating a dirt berm around the spill area and the deployment of absorbent booms and pads. Diesel fuel in trailer was transferred to another tank trailer and a third party environmental response company was dispatched to the site to handle the product release and clean-up.
column169: Drivers have been reminded of the hazards associated with winter driving conditions and the need to continually evaluate road conditions and to adjust driving according to conditions.

column168: On 12-11-14 at 1:15 pm, a company driver arrived at the Chemical Waste Management Sulphur, Louisiana facility had a product delivery line fail and release waste ash to the ground.  The waste ash was released due to a failure in modified unload coupling during dry bulk delivery.  The approximate amount of ash released was 1,000 pounds. The released material was on-site over secondary containment area.  Released material was cleaned by site personnel.
column169: Clamp was not standard installation on unit.  It was modified several years earlier by unknown location.  This modification was returned to standard acceptable design.  Possible failure hazard was not recognized by driver or maintenance personnel.

column168: CARRIER AT CONSIGNEE TO OFF LOAD, CHECKED BOTH OFF LOADING TANKS FOR SPACE AND HYDRO, HOOKED UP TO TANKS, 8 MINUTES LEFT TO COMPLETE OF LOADING AND NOTICE SMOKING COMING FROM BEHIND TANKS. CARRIER RAN, SHUT OFF TRAILER AND RAN BEHIND BULK TANKS NOTICED HAZARDOUS PRODUCT SPILLING FROM BULK TANK. CARRIER AND CONSIGNEE EMPLOYEES FOUND THE VALVE RUNNING FROM SOUTH TANK TO NORTH TANK WAS CLOSED. CONSIGNEE DOES NOT KNOW WHO OR WHY THE VALVE IS CLOSED. CONSIGNEE WILL COMPLETE CLEAN UP SPILL, 20 GALLONS INTO CONTAINMENT PIT WITH 8FT OF LIME ROCK TO NEUTRALIZES ACID. EVENT #44360.

column168: ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED, THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED. ONE 55-GALLON DRUM TIPPED IN TRANSIT, WHICH RESULTED IN THE RELEASE OF APPROXIMATELY 12 GALLONS OF FREE PRODUCT.  PRODUCT WAS CONTAINED TO THE PALLET AND TRAILER FLOOR, AND DID NOT IMPACT THE GROUND SURFACE OR THREATEN TO IMPACT STATE WATERS. ES&H ENVIRONMENTAL OF GRAND PRAIRIE, TEXAS WAS DISPATCHED TO PERFORM THE CLEANUP. ES&H ENVIRONMENTAL APPLIED ABSORBENT PADS TO THE AFFECTED AREA, WHICH WERE RECOVERED AND PLACED INTO ONE 55-GALLON DRUM. ES&H ENVIRONMENTAL PROCEEDED TO NEUTRALIZE THE IMPACTED SURFACES, AND APPLY A GRANULAR ABSORBENT TO THE AREA, WHICH WAS WORKED IN AND RECOVERED. ALL SPENT ABSORBENT PADS AND GRANULAR ABSORBENT WERE PLACED INTO THE ONE 55-GALLON DRUM, PENDING DISPOSAL IN ACCORDANCE WITH LOCAL, STATE AND FEDERAL REGULATIONS. ONE 55-GALLON DRUM WAS TRANSPORTED BY ES&H ENVIRONMENTAL TO ABILENE ENVIRONMENTAL LANDFILL IN ABILENE, TEXAS FOR DISPOSAL. THERE WERE NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES REPORTED.
column169: ROADRUNNER TRANSPORTATION SERVICES, INC. WILL CONTINUE TO TRAIN AND REINFORCE SAFE HANDLING PROCEDURES AND DRIVER SAFETY TO ALL PERSONNEL.

column168: R&L Carriers was transporting a large battery with an approximate weight of 2500 lbs. The pallet that the battery was staged on gave way and caused the battery to fall over. The battery was not damaged but approximately 1 gallon of the battery acid leaked out on to the trailer floor. A long-arm tow motor was dispatched to the site to upright the battery. The released battery acid was neutralized with soda ash and collected for disposal. The battery was placed on a replacement skid and secured for continued transport.

column62: Improper Preparation for Transportation; Too Much Weight on Package
column168: Container was reported to be leaking a paint related material from within onto the ground through wooden flooring of container.  Inspection revealed container to be loaded with 26 pallets of 5 gallon pails of paint stacked on top of each other.  7 pails were found to have been ruptured due to excessive weight from being stacked upon and no blocking and bracing.  Additionally, there were markings on the pails indicating Do Not Stack.  Ruptured pails were over packed for appropriate disposal.  Spill was remediated with recovery of paint.  Pallets were properly reloaded, blocked and braced into container.
column169: Observe and comply with do not stack markings on packages; properly block and brace load using BOE Pamphlet 6C Guide.

column14: CO HWY34 & Washington CO RD DD
column168: Driver was headed west on CO HWY 34 approaching Akron, CO.  The road ahead had just been closed due to numerous accidents (it was snowy and icy).  The Akron fire department was diverting vehicles off the HWY at Road DD. As the driver was making a right hand turn onto a road that hadn't been plowed the turn was misjudged and the trailer tires caught the edge of the adjacent ditch and were pulled into the ditch.  This caused the tractor to come to a stop and it was pulled into the ditch by the trailer resulting in an overturn.  The tractor and trailer ended up on their right hand side. The drive was not injured, he was checked over on site by the local fire department and dismissed.  As a result of the rollover, the outlet valve was broken off and due to the tank being on it's side the fire valve was slightly dislodged resulting in a small leak.  An emergency response team was called in to cut a hole in the side of the trailer so that the load could be pumped to another trailer.  Due to the weather and closed roads this took several hours to complete.  The leak continued for approximately 9 hours and approximately 300-350 gallons of ethanol were lost into the ditch.  The remediation company is working on the cleanup process and have been delayed by the ever changing weather and will be completed as soon as safely possible.
column169: This is primarily due to being in the wrong place at the wrong time and driver error.  Had the road ahead not been closed, traffic would not have been diverted onto road DD, and the accident would not have taken place.  We constantly stress safety and continued training takes place monthly for our drivers.  The involved driver had been advised to be more conscious of the environment and ever changing situation and off tracking of trailers.

column168: BRENNTAG DRIVER NOTICED LIQUID COMING OUT OF TRAILER SO HE STOPPED AND INSPECTED.  HE DETERMINED AN IBC STRAPED NEAR THE BACK OF THE TRAILER WAS CRACKED AND LEAKING.  HE REPORTED THIS TO COMPANY MANAGEMENT AND THEN RECEIVED HELP FROM OTHERS TO AVOID RUN OFF. PRODUCT FROZE ON ROAD AND CURB IN A TWO FOOT WIDE STRETCH. COMPANY MANAGEMENT CALLED FOR A THIRD PARTY ENVIRONMENTAL CLEAN UP BY CURA EMERGENCY SERVICES AND TWO EMPLOYEES WENT TO SCENE TO SIT WITH DRIVER DURING CLEAN UP.  THE "RIGID POLY IBC" IN PICTURE CRACKED ALONGSIDE WALL. CLEAN UP INCLUDED DRUMMING OFF REMAINING PRODUCT IN IBC WITH CURRENT RETEST DATE 8/12/13. ALSO OIL DRY WAS USED FOR ABSORBENT, ALONG WITH OTHER METHODS OF CLEAN UP. DURATION OF 9.5 HOURS, PHMSA FIELD INSPECTOR TIFFANY ZIEMER ON 12-10-14 COMMENTED THAT THE CONTAINER HAD REACHED ITS USEFUL LIFE EXPECTANCY AND CRACKED.
column169: THE BRENNTAG GREAT LAKES PROCEDURE 6020.12 WAS REVIEWED AND WAS FOLLOWED WHEN THIS IBC WAS FILLED. THE EMPLOYEES INVOLVED HAD RECORDS OF HAZMAT TRAINING AND WERE INVOLVED IN A TEACHING MOMENT AGAIN WITH THEIR SUPERVISOR 12-5-14. THE LOADERS AND DRIVERS ALL DID THE INSPECTIONS REQUIRED PRIOR TO THE DRIVER LEAVING THE SHIPPING LOCATION AND DRIVING 10 MILES WITH THE PROPERLY SECURED IBC UNTIL NOTICING THE LEAK, MORE NORMAL TOTE INSPECTION TEACHING DONE 12-10-14 AND ON OTHER IBC FAILED INSPECTION AND WAS TAKEN OUT OF SERVICE. BRENNTAG CONTINUES TO REPLACE OLDER IBC'S WITH NEWER ONES.

column168: POWER UNIT BEGAN TO "RUNAWAY" FROM GAS FUMES ENTERING THROUGH THE AIR INTAKE ON THE POWER UNIT.  FIRE IGNITED FROM AN UNKNOWN AREA OF THE POWER UNIT. column169: WE ARE GOING TO INSTALL INTAKE SHUTOFF VALVES ON THE POWER.  UNITS TO PROVIDE EMERGENCY OVERSPEED SHUTDOWN PROTECTION FOR DIESEL ENGINES TO PREVENT A "RUNAWAY" SITUATION.  THE VALVES COMPLETELY BLOCK THE ENGINE AIR INTAKE SYSTEM OF THE POWER UNIT, CUTTING OFF AN UNCONTROLLED EXTERNAL VAPOR FUEL SOURCE AND THE AIR REQUIRED TO KEEP THE ENGINE RUNNING.  THE MODEL AND MAKE OF THE THIS APPARATUS IS MADE BY RODA DEACO.

column168: THE TRAILER (VAN) WAS LOADED IN AMARILLO, TX WITH SEVEN (7) TOTES OF UN1993 (CLASS 3) AND THREE (3) TOTES OF UN2920 (CLASS 8). DRIVER DEPARTED FOR KILGORE, TX. HE PULLED INTO THE QUANAH, TX REST AREA AND NOTICED LIQUID LEAKING OFF THE PASSENGER'S SIDE, REAR TRUCK TIRES. HE CHECKED THE TRAILER AND LIQUID WAS COMING OUT OF THE TRAILER. HE CALLED 911. THE FIRE DEPART AND THE MT. VERNON HAZMAT CREW CAME OUT TO THE SCENE. TALON LPE (EMERGENCY SPILL RESPONSE) WAS NOTIFIED AND CAME TO THE SITE.  TALON REMOVED THE VESSELL IDENTIFIED CAUSING THE LEAK. EACH VESSEL HAD A TWO (2) INCH BALL VALVE LOCATED AT ONE SIDE AND ON THE BOTTOM WITH A GUARD TO PREVENT ANY DAMAGE DUE TO FORKLIFT LOADING OR UNLOADING. THIS GUARD, COUPLED WITH THE PLACEMENT ALONG THE TRAILER WALL, PREVENTED MANUAL ACCESS TO CLOSING OR OPENING OF THE VALVE TO STOP THE RELEASE. UPON REMOVAL, VISUAL INSPECTION IDENTIFIED THE BALL VALVE WAS SLIGHTLY OPEN AND UPON COMPLETE CLOSURE, THE RELEASED CEASED.
column169: MOST SHIPPERS WON'T ALLOW DRIVERS ON THEIR LOADING DOCKS WHILE LOADING TRAILERS.  THIS IS ESPECIALLY TRUE WITH HAZMAT LOADS. DRIVERS DON'T HAVE THE OPPORTUNITY TO SEE/INSPECT THE LOAD. IN SITUATIONS WHERE CONTAINERS ARE LOADED WITH HAZMAT THAT HAVE VALVES ON THEM, THERE SHOULD BE A SEAL/TIE HOLDING THE HANDLE OF THE VALVE IN THE CLOSED POSITION ALONG WITH A STATEMENT SIGN BY THE SHIPPER/LOADER STATING THE CONTAINER WAS INSPECTED/CHECKED AND FOUND TO BE SAFE FOR TRANSPORTATION AND ALL VALVES HAVE BEEN SECURED IN THE CLOSED POSITION.

column168: DRIVER EXITED INTERSTATE 55 NORTH TO HAMMOND, LA IN THE DIRECTION OF INTERSTATE 12 EAST.  NEAR THE END OF THE RAMP APPROACHING INTERSTATE 12, THE TRUCK AND TRAILER ROLLED OVER TO THE LEFT AND CAME TO REST ON ITS SIDE, ACROSS THE ROADWAY OF INTERSTATE 12 EAST. STATE POLICE SHUT I-12 EAST AND WEST DOWN.  FIRE DEPARTMENT ARRIVED ON THE SCENE AND SPRAYED BOOM TO CONTAIN THE GASOLINE THAT WAS LEAKING FROM THE TANK TRAILER.  THE LEFT SIDE OF THE TRAILER WAS MASHED FLAT FROM THE IMPACT AND THE ALUMINUM SHELL WAS ABRADED AS THE TRAILER SLID ACROSS THE PAVEMENT ON ITS SIDE.  THE ABRASION CAUSED SEVERAL HOLES IN THE SHELL APPROXIMATELY 1/2 INCH WIDE AND 3 INCHES LONG.  THE GASOLINE POURED OUT THROUGH THE HOLES UNTIL THE TANK WAS NEARLY EMPTY.  THE RELEASE OF THE PRODUCT OCCURRED FOR APPROXIMATELY 4 HOURS.  WITH THE APPLICATION OF THE BOOM, THE GASOLINE WAS RETAINED IN THE DITCH.  VACUUM TRUCKS VACUUMED THE DITCH OUT.  THE GASOLINE IMPACTED SOIL WAS REPLACED BY CLEAN, NON-CONTAMINATED SOIL.

column168: TRUCK TRANSPORTING CRUDE OIL WAS TRAVELING SOUTHBOUND ON A DIRT ROAD WITH A SLIGHT BEND. A TRUCK TRAVELING NORTHBOUND CROWDED TOO MUCH OF THE ROAD FORCING THE SOUTHBOUND CRUDE TRUCK TO CROWD THE SHOULDER. THIS ACTION CAUSED THE TRUCK TO CUT THE CORNER SHORT IN THE BEND IN THE ROAD. STEEP/SOFT DIRT SHOULDERS COMBINED WITH THE LANE VIOLATION CAUSED THE TRUCK TO OVERTURN. DURING THE OVERTURNING, THE GIRARD VALVE ON TOP OF THE TRAILER WAS CRACKED WHICH RESULTED IN LEAKAGE FROM THE TRAILER. EMS WAS CALLED AND TRANSPORTED THE DRIVER TO THE HOSPITAL. NOW OR NEVER DISPATCHED ANOTHER DRIVER TO OFF-LOAD THE CRUDE. CUSTOM ENVIRONMENTAL SEVICES WAS ALSO DISPATCHED WITHIN 30 MINUTES OF THE INCIDENT. CES WAS ON SCENE, DUE TO THE REMOTE LOCATION OF THE INCIDENT. CES CONTAINED WHAT HAD BEEN RELEASED. THE TRUCK WAS GROUNDED AND OFF-LOADED, COMPLETE CLEANUP FOLLOWED DAYS LATER DUE TO ADVERSE WEATHER CONDITIONS.

IN THE EARLY MORNING HOURS OF FRIDAY, DECEMBER 5TH, AT APPROXIMATELY 3:30AM EST, AN ECO ENERGY DRIVER ENTERED THE RYDER GREENSBORO FACILITY (#0134) LOCATED AT 217 ATEWLL AVENUE, UNLOCKING THE SECURITY COMBINATION LOCK AT THE GATE AND PARKING EQUIPMENT ON THE RYDER YARD.  HE BROUGHT THE COMBINATION TRACTOR/TRAILER EQUIPMENT TO THE RYDER FACILITY FOR REPAIRS AFTER DISCOVERING THAT A BACK WINDOW OF THE TRACTOR CAB HAD BEEN BROKEN DURING TRANSIT.  THE DRIVER PARKED THE TRACTOR AND LOADED TANKER TRAILER ONSITE, LOCKED THE VEHICLE AND THEN LEFT THE SITER USING HIS PERSONAL AUTOMOBILE THAT WAS PARKED AT THE RYDER FACILITY.  THE RYDER FACILITY WAS CLOSED WHEN THE VEHICLE WAS PARKED.  THE SHOP HOURS OF OPERATION ARE MONDAY THRU FRIDAY FROM 6AM TO 11PM.  THE SHOP OPENED A FEW HOURS LATER AT APPROXIMATELY 6:00AM.  AT APPROXIMATELY 9:00AM, THE DRIVER CALLED THE RYDER FACILITY TO ADVISE THAT HE HAD LEFT THE VEHICLE AND TO REPORT NEEDED REPAIRS TO THE SHOP MAINTENANCE PERSONAL BUT THE DRIVER NEGLECTED TO MENTION THAT THE TANKER WAS FULL OF
column169: RYDER AND ECOENERGY HAVE COLLABORATED TO INVESTIGATE THE INCIDENT AND IMPLEMENT IMPROVED COMMUNICATIONS, EMPLOYEE AWARENESS AND MANAGEMENT PRACTICES.  EACH COMPANY HAS FOCUSED ON REFINING WRITTEN PROCEDURES, RE-TRAINING EMPLOYEES, REDISTRIBUTING POLICIES AND REINFORCING EXISTING PROCEDURES NECESSARY TO ENSURE THAT NO LOADED TANKERS ARE BROUGHT TO RYDER OR LEFT UNATTENDED.  A SAMPLE OF SOME OF THESE EFFORTS IS PROVIDED BELOW:    ECO ENERGY ACTION  * ROLLED OUT REVISED WRITTEN POLICIES WHICH EXPLICITLY ADDRESS AND OUTLINE REQUIREMENTS OF DRIVERS, DISPATCHERS, AND ECO-ENERGY TRANSPORTATION MANAGEMENT AS IT RELATES TO THE PARKING AND ATTENDANCE OF LOADED TANKERS AND VEHICLES; FOCUSING SPECIFICALLY ON TANKERS THAT ARE LOADED AND CONFIRMING THAT DRIVERS CANNOT LEAVE LOADED TANKERS AT ANY TIME. THESE POLICIES ARE DESIGNED TO RETRAIN AND REINFORCE AWARENESS, CLARIFY REQUIREMENTS, AS WELL AS ELEVATE PENALTIES FOR FAILURE TO COMPLY.    * VICE PRESIDENT OF TRANSPORTATION DELIVERING REFRESHER TRAINING TO ALL TEAM MEMBERS AT MULTIPLE SITES, TO INCLUDE EVERY DRIVER, DISPATCHER, AND MEMBER OF ECO-ENERGY TRANSPORTATION MANAGEMENT TEAM REGARDING EXISTING AND NEW POLICIES RELATING TO PARKING AND ATTENDANCE OF VEHICLES DURING TRANSIT, EMERGENCY REPAIRS AND PARKED EQUIPMENT; PARTICULARLY WHILE LOADED.    * PROVIDED ENHANCED TRAINING TO DISPATCHERS REGARDING APPROPRIATE STEPS TO PREVENT THE POSSIBILITY OF A LOADED TRAILER BEING LEFT UNATTENDED, INCLUDING ADDITIONAL SUPPORT RESOURCES WHEN ALL OTHERS HAVE BEEN EXHAUSTED.

column168: During baggage screening, TSA discovered the leaking can of paint in the Customers checked bag.  The Can and liquid were contained in a plastic ziplock bag.

AT APPROXIMATELY 2:25 HAZMAT RECEIVED A CALL OF A LEAKING HAZARDOUS MATERIAL PACKAGE IN THE LOADING AREA THE DESIGNATED RESPONDER KELLY WEAVER RESPONDED TO THE CALL WEARING FULL PPE AND PROCEEDED TO CLEAN THE SPILLED MATERIAL AND PLACE THE PACKAGE ALONG WITH THE DEBRIS FROM THE CLEAN UP WAS PLACED INTO A LINED SPILL TRAY. SHE THEN TRANSPORTED THE PACKAGE AND CONTAMINATED DEBRIS TO THE SERVICE CENTER WHERE IT WAS PROCESSED THROUGH THE DMP BY DESIGNATED RESPONDER MARCUS JOHNSON
